collections.name: 2025 April
collections.description:
MintDay – The NFT That Shares Its Own Birthday

A one-of-a-kind NFT collection where each piece is minted on the exact day it represents. A real birthday, a real date, a real-time creation—all aligning in a single moment. Every NFT is a true snapshot of time, forever linking the artwork to the day it was born.

Time moves forward, and each moment passes—gone, but not lost. This collection lets you hold onto that day, even as time moves on.

MintDay is also an exploration of how creative thought evolves day by day. Sometimes the shifts are subtle, almost imperceptible; other times, they push beyond established boundaries. In a way, this project reflects the life of form—a continuous journey of artistic thinking, unfolding in real time.

Each MintDay marks a unique digital birth, capturing the significance of that exact moment. Once a day is gone, it can never be minted again.

One day. One NFT. One chance.
Once it’s gone, it’s gone.
2025 April

MetaMelt Faces
collections.description:
“Cold Metal, Warm Faces.”（冷たい金属、温かい顔たち。）

MetaMelt Faces

MetaMelt Faces are the inhabitants of the metaverse where metal and emotions merge. Though metal is supposed to be cold and rigid, it melts into expressive forms, bringing each face to life as if infused with a soul. This collection is a fusion of the inorganic and the organic—a new kind of 3D art that challenges perception.

Each MetaMelt Face has been programmed with “emotions,” evolving beyond mere metal constructs to become self-aware beings.

Every face carries a unique emotion and story—joy, surprise, confusion, anger, and more. While their bodies remain metallic, their expressions are unexpectedly warm and full of personality. This contrast between hardness and softness makes them uniquely charming, bridging the gap between machine and humanity.

collections.name: Luther's Root
collections.description:
Luther

I was just a quiet boy who loved to draw.
When I was in middle school, I won first place in a school art contest,
even surpassing senior students from the art club.

My teacher believed in me and wanted me to pursue art seriously.
He even offered to support my full tuition to art school.

But we didn’t come from a wealthy family, and my parents were worried it would be too much.
So, I let go of that dream and chose a different path.

Many years later, I began drawing again—not for fame,
but to tell gentle stories to my child through images.

My art centers on trees, through which I explore the human world, memory, and quiet reflections.
This NFT work is not a comeback.
It is a reunion—with the boy I once was,
and the dream I quietly held for so long.

collections.name: Venom & Vice
collections.description:
Venom & Vice aka Poison NFT takes a deep dive into how alcohol is in fact poison and if it was marketed correctly as such.

Alcohol is a poison because it is a toxic substance that negatively affects nearly every system in the body. When consumed, the body treats alcohol as a toxin and prioritizes metabolizing it over other nutrients to eliminate it as quickly as possible. The liver plays a primary role in breaking down alcohol, but excessive consumption can overwhelm this process, leading to toxic byproducts like acetaldehyde, which damages cells and tissues.

Why Alcohol is Poisonous:

1. Toxic Effects on the Body – Alcohol is a depressant that slows brain function, impairs judgment, and reduces motor skills. At high doses, it can cause respiratory failure, coma, or death.
2. Liver Damage – Chronic alcohol use leads to fatty liver, hepatitis, fibrosis, and cirrhosis, which are progressive and often irreversible conditions.
3. Brain Damage – Alcohol kills brain cells & shrinks brain🧠

collections.name: NO PARKING IN SHALLOW WATER by ABOSCH
collections.description: NO PARKING IN SHALLOW WATER (2025) – 36 works by conceptual artist Kevin Abosch that hybridize the decaying elegance of vintage automobiles with the stillness of shallow (and sometimes empty) pools. These synthetic photographs examine symbols of freedom and leisure, recontextualizing them into compositions that drift between landscape and still life. The series confronts the quiet violence of nostalgia --how decay, when framed as charm or legacy, becomes a tool for erasure, and how a longing for what once was can be weaponized to obscure what is.
